body:
@guozhangwang  

Changes made per review comments.

EDIT: do we want to create a separate jira ticket to circle back through the tests and update all Consumer/Producer/Stream Configs useage to use helper methods in TestUtils/StreamTestUtils ?

> Also, seems like I was late adding my comments. They can be addressed in a follow-up PR once there is agreement.

@ijuma   cc: @guozhangwang 

Thanks for the additional feedback, should I address these issues in a new Jira ticket?

@hachikuji, I think that yes, I would create a ConsumerMetrics class that would collect all the metrics for the consumer, and a ProducerMetrics class for all the producer. There may also be ConnectMetrics and StreamsMetrics.

There is at least one class (Selector) that is used by both the consumer and the producer. I will need to find a way to make it so that the Selector class creates the right metrics objects at the right time. In other words, that Selector instantiates the ConsumerMetrics objects when called via the consumer, and the ProducerMetrics objects when called via the producer.

I'll flesh out this proof of concept some more, and make sure that it'll work.

>  creating lots of short-lived objects (some may move to old-gen if it last too long?),

I'd say this is relatively very small cost that all `KafkaProducer` users should accept.
In terms of short-lived objects there are already lots of objects created during producing record, which makes a callback object relatively smaller than them.
Indeed they could live much longer than we expect during potentially long `linger.ms` or maybe during retrying due to the broker failure but still we can't say that instantiating callback on each send could be the point of optimization to reduce GC pressure I guess.

> by returning the RecordMetadata still if exception != null but without the timestamp and offset values. 

I agree with that this could be a better interface but since the current behavior was there even as of 0.8.X, I have concern to change it now.
It is not declared as an interface signature explicitly but I'd say most users implicitly expecting `metadata` is null when producing failed.
This change breaks behavior compatibility if a user wrote a code like below, which shouldn't be considered as solved just by leaving an upgrade note.

``` java
producer.send(..., (metadata, exception) -> {
    if (metadata == null) {
        // Error handling
    }
});
```

So my opinion is, even though we want to make that change eventually, that should be done with the next major version release(0.11.X).

Thoughts?
